      "title": "Condition for one common root",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Common Roots</strong></h3><p>(1) Only one root is common</p><p>Let <i>Î± </i>be the common root of quadratic equations ${{a}_{1}}{{x}^{2}}+{{b}_{1}}x+{{c}_{1}}=0$ and ${{a}_{2}}{{x}^{2}}+{{b}_{2}}x+{{c}_{2}}=0$.</p><p>âˆ´ ${{a}_{1}}{{\\alpha }^{2}}+{{b}_{1}}\\alpha +{{c}_{1}}=0$, ${{a}_{2}}{{\\alpha }^{2}}+{{b}_{2}}\\alpha +{{c}_{2}}=0$</p><p>By Crammerâ€™s rule : $\\frac{{{\\alpha }^{2}}}{\\left| \\,\\begin{matrix} -{{c}_{1}} &amp; {{b}_{1}} \\\\ -{{c}_{2}} &amp; {{b}_{2}} \\\\ \\end{matrix}\\, \\right|}=\\frac{\\alpha }{\\left| \\,\\begin{matrix} {{a}_{1}} &amp; -{{c}_{1}} \\\\ {{a}_{2}} &amp; -{{c}_{2}} \\\\ \\end{matrix}\\, \\right|}=\\frac{1}{\\left| \\,\\begin{matrix} {{a}_{1}} &amp; {{b}_{1}} \\\\ {{a}_{2}} &amp; {{b}_{2}} \\\\ \\end{matrix}\\, \\right|}$ or $\\frac{{{\\alpha }^{2}}}{{{b}_{1}}{{c}_{2}}-{{b}_{2}}{{c}_{1}}}=\\frac{\\alpha }{{{a}_{2}}{{c}_{1}}-{{a}_{1}}{{c}_{2}}}=\\frac{1}{{{a}_{1}}{{b}_{2}}-{{a}_{2}}{{b}_{1}}}$</p><p>âˆ´ $\\alpha =\\frac{{{a}_{2}}{{c}_{1}}-{{a}_{1}}{{c}_{2}}}{{{a}_{1}}{{b}_{2}}-{{a}_{2}}{{b}_{1}}}=\\frac{{{b}_{1}}{{c}_{2}}-{{b}_{2}}{{c}_{1}}}{{{a}_{2}}{{c}_{1}}-{{a}_{1}}{{c}_{2}}}$, $\\alpha \\ne 0$</p><p>âˆ´ The condition for only one root common is</p><p>${{({{c}_{1}}{{a}_{2}}-{{c}_{2}}{{a}_{1}})}^{2}}=({{b}_{1}}{{c}_{2}}-{{b}_{2}}{{c}_{1}})({{a}_{1}}{{b}_{2}}-{{a}_{2}}{{b}_{1}})$</p><p>(2) Both roots are common:</p><p>Then required condition is</p><p>$\\frac{{{a}_{1}}}{{{a}_{2}}}=\\frac{{{b}_{1}}}{{{b}_{2}}}=\\frac{{{c}_{1}}}{{{c}_{2}}}$</p>",
